The R² gap between Model A and Model B quantifies how much runtime variance requires runtime-observable signals to explain but does not capture the gap from memory bandwidth constraints versus compute constraints. The roofline model is used to address the gap directly by establishing theoretical peak performance bounds for neural network operators relative to the T4 hardware ceilings. The achievable operational throughput of an operator is limited by the minimum between the peak computational throughput of the accelerator or the product of the accelerator’s memory bandwidth and arithmetic intensity AI. 
AI=F/Q
T_roof=min(P_peak,B_peak×F/Q)
Where T_roof represents the expected execution time under ideal conditions,  F represents the total arithmetic volume, Q represents the total memory bandwidth
Total Arithmetic Volume F is defined as the algorithmic FLOP count derived from a product of operator dimensions and expected FLOP count. A static definition is used for consistency with prior work therefore each operator class uses a closed form expression for arithmetic volume. For example, in batched matrix multiplication (BMM) operator with dimensions (B,M,N,K) is defined as 2×B×M×N×K, corresponding to a multiply and add for each arithmetic step. 
Total Memory Bandwidth Q is defined as the number of bytes transferred between off-chip memory and the accelerator from each operator execution. To statically define Q the byte volume from all tensors read from written memory are summed. In BMM, LLC → DRAM traffic occurs during input activation reads, weight reads, and output activations writes. Consequently, the total memory volume moved can me modeled as Q=(BMK+BKN+BMN)  ×s_pre where  s_pre represents the number of bytes at a given precision level. 
In tile specific rooflines, both F and Q are uniformly distributed to tile level compute volume F_tile and memory volume Q_tile. Deriving F and Q statically from operator geometry is the standard practice based on prior roofline modeling frameworks (Wen et al., 2025) (Wess et al., 2021). Neural network operators have deterministic mathematic structure, the model’s total number of floating-point operations and tensor elements accessed are defined entirely by the algorithm regardless of the underly accelerator architecture.
